Introduction & Background

I’ll introduce Bayesian statistical modeling via an example

  • Today I’ll discuss a hierachical (multi-level) Bayesian model
  • This model will analyze data from Dr. Jiang’s Plasticity Lab
  • The data arise from experiments studying Temporal Recalibration.

Scientific background

  • Our temporal perception can be modified by contextual factors (ex. adapting to some temporal delay in the environment) and by biological factors (ex. aging).

  • With varying levels of temporal perception, it is difficult to determine which aspects are altered by aging.

Main research questions (spoiler: we won’t answer these today)

  • How does aging affect different types of temporal judgments?
  • How does threshold (temporal sensitivity) change as a function of age?
  • How does age affect temporal recalibration?

Experimental design

  • 4 tasks were given to subjects. But today we highlight the Audio-Visual (AV) task.
  • The AV task presents two stimuli — an audio cue and a visual cue.
  • The task for the subject is to determine which came first.
  • Subjects were tested on a range of temporal delays that separated two stimuli. These are referred to as stimulus onset asynchronies (SOAs).

AV task explained

SOAs: -500 to +500 ms with 50 ms steps

Subjects

  • Young age group, n = 14, 18 – 30 years old
  • Middle age group, n = 15, 40 – 50 years old
  • Older age group, n = 15, 65 – 75 years old

Statistical modeling

It’s possible to fit an “S-shaped” curve

Bayesian Statistics 101

  • Bayesian statistics is a mathematical formalization of learning from data.
  • We use variables (called parameters) to model quantities of interest.
  • These parameters are unobservable and we are *uncertain** of their values.
  • So we treat them as random variables and give probaibilities to their values.

Bayesian Statistics 101

  • Bayes’ rule combines our prior knowledge of the parameters with the data at hand.
  • The result is a new probability distribution, called the posterior that reflects our updated beliefs.
  • Bayes’ rule can be summarized as

\(posterior \propto (prior) \times (likelihood)\).
